This project addressed the fascinating and understudied problem of how environmental cues influence developmental processes to cause phenotypic diversity and, importantly, how those processes evolve. Work focused on a textbook example of phenotypic plasticity in aphids, in which dramatically different winged and wingless morphs are produced depending on environmental conditions. Variation for this wing morph plasticity exists within natural populations and between emerging species adapting to different host plants, providing a powerful framework for examining the evolution of this ecologically-relevant trait.


Major intellectual merit research outcomes of this award include:


(1)Discovering dopamine as a key modulator of the pea aphid wing plasticity;


(2)Identifying a laterally transferred gene as important in plasticity variation within species;


(3)Finding that the wing plasticity response differs within and among pea aphid subspecies;


(4)Determining that likely many genes underlie wing plasticity variation;


(5)Characterizing how environmental impacts during development can lead to alterations in not only morph production, but also trait asymmetries, trait integration, and trait fluctuating asymmetry.


Overall, the work provided a detailed picture of the overall variation for this trait available to natural selection and showed that many different molecular genetic mechanisms underlie it.


Activities under the award also provided professional development activities to trainees (postdocs and PhD students) that were geared to their intended careers in science. Undergraduates participated in meaningful research experiences that led to co-authorships on publications. Broader impacts included working to make a genetic course involve more active learning approaches and partnering with the local Upward Bound Program to provide summer hands-on workshops and internships to high school students.


